[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/process-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/process-designer-6-7)

The *Properties* view displays different types of properties, depending on the selection in the editor or view which is currently in focus. For each property type there is a separate tab. The tabs are listed top to bottom on the left side of the view. The visibility and the content of the tabs depend on the selection within the workbench.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 6. Properties View*

## **Main**
The *Main* tab displays and provides editing for the basic properties of process components and is visible if a component is selected in the editor or the *Outline* view. Below is a list of the properties contained in this tab and their purpose. The text in braces, next to the name states for which components the property is available.

- *ID* (all components): The id for a component. Must always have a value and has to be unique within the process (components in groups count as separate processes).

- *Name* (all components): The name for a process component. Optional.

- *From* (connection, exception connection): Source element of the connection. Cannot be changed.

- *To* (connection, exception connection): Target element of the connection. Cannot be changed.

- *Save Point* (connection, exception connection): Sets a save point on this connection.

- *Conditions* (decision): Table containing all conditions for the decision. Each condition belongs to a connection, so the number of rows in the table is always equal to the number of outgoing connections of the decision. The *Connection* column shows the id of the Connection, the condition belongs to. Click on a row in the *expression* column to change the expression of the condition. The order of the conditions can be changed using drag and drop, the *Move Up* and *Move Down* entries in the context menu or shortcuts.

- *Condition* (connection originating from decision): The expression for the condition of the decision belonging to this connection.

- *Condition* (other elements): Optional condition which determines if this element should be executed.

- *Descriptor* (activities): The type of activity used by this activity element. Editing is disabled by default, because in most cases users select the activity type from the palette when creating the element. Editing can be enabled by clicking the button next to the text field.

- *Language* (script): The language of the script.

- *Script Url* (script): The URL of the script. If this property is set, the *Script Code* field must be empty.

- *Script Code* (script): The code of the script. If this property is set, the *Script Url* field must be empty.

- *Type* (wait element): The type of wait state to use.

- *Type* (exception connection): The type of exception which should be caught.

- *Type* (task element): The type of task used by this task element. Editing is disabled by default, because in most cases users select the task type from the palette when creating the element. Editing can be enabled by clicking the button next to the text field.

- *Retries* (exception connection): The number of times the process should take this exception connection before throwing the exception.

- *Delay* (connection, exception connection): Time in milliseconds to delay before continuing via this connection.

- *Process* (Include Process): Path of the process file to include, relative to the containing process file.

- *Uncache* (wait element, task element): Specifies whether the process execution should be removed from the cache once the process is waiting.

- *Store Credentials* (task element): Specifies whether the task should store the credentials of a user who does a checkin.

- *Default Thread Pool* (process): Optional name of the default thread pool in which this process should be executed if no thread pool is provided as a parameter during instantiation.

## Log
![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 7. Log Properties Tab*

The *Log* tab provides capabilities for defining diagnostic log messages and data log messages in the process. It is visible if a process element or the process itself is selected in the editor or *Outline* view

### Diagnostic Log
Each process element has a *Log Before* line and a *Log After* line (exceptions are start and end element which only have one) at the top of the *Log* tab. Define a log message by selecting the log level from the combo box and entering the message in the text field next to it. Note that a log message always requires a log level, if the log level is set to *none*, the message will not be persisted in the process. The diagnostic log messages can also be set for the process itself. Select the process by clicking on the background of the editor area.

### Data Log
For the process elements which can also have a data log, the *Log* tab also contains a data log section below the diagnostic log messages. To define data logging first select a log level. If the log level is set to *none*, specifying data for logging does not work. Add and delete data using the *Add* and *Delete* button on the right side next to the table. Define the name of the data by typing it in the text field in the *Name* column. Define the data by typing it in the text field in the *Data* column.

## Note
The *Note* tab is only visible if a note is selected in the editor. It provides a text field where the text of the note is displayed and can be edited.

## Execution
The *Process Execution* tab shows detailed information about a process execution started from Process Designer. It is visible if an execution is selected in the *Process Execution List* view. The title at the top shows a message which reflects the state of the process. Below is a list of the fields in this tab including a description of what information they display.

*Fields*

- *Process*: The URL of the process file.

- *Config*: The name of the launch configuration used to start the process.

- *Engine*: The name of the process Engine configuration used fr execution.

- *State*: The state of the process execution.

- *Element*: The process element which is currently executed. Empty if the process has already ended.

- *Started At*: The time the process has been started.

- *Finished At*: The time the process has ended.

- *Message*: Error message if the process has run into an error.

- *Exception*: Table showing thrown exceptions including nested ones as a tree. The *Message* column contains the exception messages, the *Type* column the exception types and the *Source* column the id of the process element where the exception occurred.

## Data
The *Data* tab is visible when an element which can contain mappings is selected in the editor. Under this tab all information regarding mappings can be edited.

For activities/tasks, there are three tabs at the top. Each of them contains a list of mappings and parameter placeholders. The *Input* tab contains only the input mappings, the *Output* tab only the output mappings and the *Input/Output* tab contains both, separated into two columns.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 8. List of input mappings in properties Data tab for an activity.*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 9. List of output mappings in properties Data tab for an activity.*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 10. List of input and output mappings in properties Data tab for an activity.*

For start, end and mapping elements only one list is shown.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 11. List of mappings in properties Data tab for a start element.*

New mappings can be created by clicking the *Add Mapping* button at the bottom of the list. Next to it on the right there is another Button for adding Keep-Variables Mappings.

The design and layout of the mappings and placeholders in the list matches those used in the editor in data mode. They look and work similar to their counterparts in the editor, but contain more information and additional modification possibilities. The details for both components are described in the following sub-sections.

### Mappings
Mappings are represented as blue boxes containing different controls for editing. There is a full and a collapsed version of the mapping box. Switching between them can be done by clicking on the arrow symbol in front of each box. The full version of a mapping is also shown when it is selected in the editor.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 12. List of mappings in properties Data tab for a start element with the first one expanded.*

The collapsed version consists of the following components:

- Drag Handle: Used to drag the mapping for drag and drop operations. Within the properties view this can be used to change the order of the mappings in the list. If the *Ctrl* key is pressed while dropping, a duplicate is created for the dragged mapping instead of moving it. It can also be dragged beyond the properties view, making use of the general datamode drag operations. (see [Drag and Drop](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-data-mode#drag-and-drop)).

- Source type button: The icon on this button and the tooltip visible when hovering over it, indicate the current source type. Clicking the button opens a dropdown list where the type can be selected. In addition to a specific type, it can also be set to *auto*. This is the default setting and means that the type is not explicitly set, but is derived from the value provided in the source value control. How this works is described below. If the button is not set to *auto*, it is activated.

- Source value control: There are different controls for providing the value. Only one of them is visible, depending on the current source type. If the source type button is set to *auto*, the provided input defines the source type. The types, their controls and the input patterns they are derived from are listed below:

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,) Null: Text field; Chosen if the input is left empty.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,)Variable: Combobox containing list of potentially existing variables; Chosen if the input is prefixed with a "$".

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,) Variable Move: Combobox containing list of potentially existing variables; Never chosen automatically, must be chosen manually via source type button.

- ![](data:image/png;base64,) XPath: Text field with open dialog button; Chosen if input is enclosed by "{" and "}".

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,) Parameterized Literal: Text field with open dialog button; Chosen if input contains one or more pairs of "{" and "}" not enclosing the whole expression.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABwSURBVDhP7ZJtCsAgCIZr7GAe3UHHEjYUjWqhCPu5B0x7/aig8gkAcLPpNmSqzzSucG/lBRGrCZIJGOsPUQaICMxU2mrGqb7TWrs05BPE7zRjuoFdzWOteT0hyz/AGTB+KveDucmA3stBZlC23qGUB0NGQZuosa8iAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Literal: Text field with open dialog button; Chosen if no other type fits.

- ![](data:image/png;base64,) Url: Text field with open file selection dialog button; Never chosen automatically, must be chosen manually via source type button.

- Copy source value to target name: A button which copies the value of the first Mapping Source to the target name field. The same action is also accessible via context menu of the mapping.

- Target name text field: Specifies the name of the variable, this mapping creates.

- Target type combobox: Specifies the data type of the variable, this mapping creates.

In the collapsed version there are also small white icons which indicate information which can only be modified in the full version. If there is a plus symbol next to the source value control, it means that there are additional values defined which are not directly visible. Those can be either additional sources or default values. If there is a star symbol in the upper right corner of the box, it means that the mapping is required. If there is a loop symbol in the lower right corner, it means that the mapping has an iteration target.

The full version has the following additional controls:

- *Defaults* tab: Contains a field for specifying a default XPath expression and an optional list of default values for the mapping. If the expression field has content, the expression is used to derive the values and default values defined in addition are ignored. Default values can be added using the *Add* button. The value is defined by writing it into the text field. A value can be deleted using the *Delete* button next to the text field. If default values are defined the tab header shows a white plus symbol.

- *Add* button: Adds a new source to the mapping.

- *Delete* buttons: Only visible if multiple sources are present. Deletes the source it belongs to.

- Additional sources: Each source has a source type button, source value control and *Delete* button.

- *Required* checkbox: Select if the mapping should be required or not.

- *Iteration* checkbox: Select if the mapping should have an iteration target instead of a standard variable target.

A mapping can also be deleted, copied and cut, using the entries in the context menu which can be opened by right clicking on the box (Text controls have their own context menus, so you need to click on the border or the other controls within the box).

### Keep-Variables Mappings
While regular mappings have a variable target, keep-variables mappings always have a keepvariables target, which clears the target pipeline and retains only the variables provided by the sources, when executed. The representation is similar to other mappings, with the difference that the box is a different shade of blue and instead of a target configuration there is just a label *KEEP*. The definition of sources and defaults works the same way as for normal mappings.

### Parameter Placeholders
Like in the editor, the parameter placeholder is shown as a light blue, rounded rectangle. If it has a red border, it is required. A mapping for the parameter can be created by double clicking it or using the *Add* button on the right. The informations within the placeholder are described below.

- Name: The parameter name. If it is an input the name is used as the target name of the created mapping. If it is an output the name is used as the source value for the variable source of the created mapping.

- Type: The data type for the parameter variable. If it is an input the type is used as target type of the created mapping.

- Min.: The minimum number of values required for this variable. If it is greater than 0, the value for this parameter must not be null, or the activity/task will fail.

- Max.: The maximum number of values allowed for this variable. If it is 1, variables with multiple values are not supported.
